The functionality of the amygdala has been explored through animal testing on rhesus monkeys, who had one side of symmetrical brain element removed and the brain’s hemispheres seperated.
The Difference in behavior was significant when either eye was covered:
With an open eye on the side of the intact amygdala, the monkeys’ reactions to potential threats or partners for (sexual) interactions were normal.
When the same eye was covered, however, the primates showed neither fear, nor aggression or empathy..

Living structures

but physics, i think, has a lot to say about living structures.

And that means that if things change with time there is information coded in there, and the information is actually processed
so whenever you have complex systems that change with time, you can call it a computer.
This is an isolated brain.
And the first thing i should say is that it is completely useless.
It only works because it interacts with the environment and with other brains.
I say that information is contained in a system like that but if you want to process it …
… if you want to make useful things it has to interact with the outside world through sensors.
Like eyes and ears and other sensors.
And of course also with other brains.

WELCOME...



This website is an interpretation of the book 333 by the artist Lukas Rehm, in which he combines his moving image works with text fragments and presents his artistic process. This work is a kind of homage to the book, which I have been studying over the last few weeks. The result is a video-like experience in which I try to make the book a digital experience. Please press play at the bottom left to start the animation and switch on the sound for the best possible experience.

The whole website is about 2.4 MB in size.

Enjoy the journey.
